title: SFH visits chilled beef processing plant and cattle farm in Changchun (with photos)
content_text:
p>
    The Secretary for Food and Health, Dr York Chow, this morning (December 7) 
    visited a chilled beef processing plant and its associated beef cattle farm 
    in Changchun to learn more about the plant's operation and production 
    facilities, as well as the management, hygiene and disease prevention 
    measures adopted by the farm. Dr Chow first visited the plant, which is registered for the processing and 
    export of chilled beef under the State General Administration of Quality 
    Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine. It will supply Mainland chilled beef

Supervision, Inspection and Quarantine. It will supply Mainland chilled beef 
    to Hong Kong. In operation since 2000, the processing plant is well equipped with 
    cleansing and disinfection facilities, and 400 beef cattle can be 
    slaughtered daily. Veterinarians are stationed at the plant for cattle 
    inspection. Dr Chow then visited the cattle farm, which opened in 2003 to provide 
    cattle, mainly to the plant. The farm is subject to inspection and 
    quarantine carried out by the Jilin Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine

quarantine carried out by the Jilin Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine 
    Bureau. The farm has put in place stringent controls regarding animal 
    hygiene and disease prevention, as well as guidelines on disinfection, 
    disease prevention measures, management of cattle and cattle feces. 
    Dedicated veterinarians are also hired to supervise and monitor hygiene and 
    disease prevention control measures at the farm.  Noting that officers of the Food and Environmental Hygiene Department had 
    already inspected the processing plant and the cattle farm, Dr Chow said it

already inspected the processing plant and the cattle farm, Dr Chow said it 
    was considered that both establishments maintain a good standard of 
    environmental hygiene, production processes, disease prevention and 
    quarantine measures. He expressed his gratitude to the staff at both 
    facilities, and hoped that they would provide Hong Kong with reasonably 
    priced chilled beef that also meets the food hygiene and safety standards. Before returning to Hong Kong this afternoon, Dr Chow met with the 
    Vice-Governor of Jilin Province, Mr Chen Waigen, and Director General of the

Jilin Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine Bureau, Mr Zhao Zhenshuan, to exchange views on issues of mutual concern. Ends/Tuesday, December 7, 2010
Issued at HKT 18:42
